qas.question: What is a central duty of the prime minister?
What is it called when a monarch has a share of executive powers?
Using royal prerogative does not require the consent of which body?
Who has no reponsibility for passing bills with the rest of the cabinet?
What is it called when the monarch has all the executive powers?
Who must consent to the use of royal perogative?

context: The <b3_0>prime minister<b3_0/> is often, but not always, a member of <a2_0>parliament<a2_0/>[clarification needed] and is expected with other ministers to <a0_0>ensure the passage of bills<a0_0/> through the legislature. In some monarchies the monarch may also exercise executive powers (known as the <a1_0><b4_0>royal prerogative<b4_0/><a1_0/>) that are constitutionally vested in the crown and may be exercised without the approval of <b5_0>parliament<b5_0/>.
